{"id":"1908.07075","submitter":"Andrey Morgulis","authors":"Andrey Morgulis, Konstantin Ilin","title":"Drift, stabilizing and destabilizing for a Patlak-Keller-Segel system\n  with the short-wavelength external signal","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"q-bio.PE nlin.PS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This article aims at exploring the short-wavelength stabilization and\ndestabilization of the advection-diffusion systems formulated using the\nPatlak-Keller-Segel cross-diffusion. We study a model of the taxis partly\ndriven by an external signal. We address the general short-wavelength signal\nusing the homogenization technique, and then we give a detailed analysis of the\nsignals emitted as the travelling waves. It turns out that homogenizing\nproduces the drift of species, which is the main translator of the external\nsignal effects, in particular, on the stability issues. We examine the\nstability of the quasi-equilibria - that is, the simplest short-wavelength\npatterns fully imposed by the external signal. Comparing the results to the\ncase of switching the signal off allows us to estimate the effect of it. For\ninstance, the effect of the travelling wave turns out to be not single-valued\nbut depending on the wave speed. Namely, there is an independent threshold\nvalue such that increasing the amplitude of the wave destabilizes the\nquasi-equilibria provided that the wave speed is above this value. Otherwise,\nthe same action exerts the opposite effect. It is worth to note that the effect\nis exponential in the amplitude of the wave in both cases.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 19 Aug 2019 21:26:50 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 2 Sep 2019 17:15:55 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 21 Aug 2020 10:58:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-08-24"}
